<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">p=
hysics</a>, an <b>electronvolt</b> (symbol <b>eV</b>), also written as <b>e=
lectron-volt</b> and <b>electron volt</b>, is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Unit_of_measurement" title=3D"Unit of measurement">unit of me=
asurement</a> equivalent to the amount of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Kinetic_energy" title=3D"Kinetic energy">kinetic energy</a> gained =
by a single <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron" title=3D"Ele=
ctron">electron</a> accelerating through an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Voltage" title=3D"Voltage">electric potential difference</a> of o=
ne <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volt" title=3D"Volt">volt</a> i=
n a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vacuum" title=3D"Vacuum">vacuu=
m</a>. When used as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Units_of_ene=
rgy" title=3D"Units of energy">unit of energy</a>, the numerical value of 1=
 eV expressed in unit of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joule" ti=
tle=3D"Joule">joules</a> (symbol J) is equal to the numerical value of the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_charge" title=3D"Electric=
 charge">charge</a> of an electron in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Coulomb" title=3D"Coulomb">coulombs</a> (symbol C). Under the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_revision_of_the_SI" title=3D"2019 re=
vision of the SI">2019 revision of the SI</a>, this sets 1&nbsp;eV equal to=
 the exact value <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6981160217=
663400000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.602<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">176</spa=
n><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">634</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0=
.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9219</sup>&nbsp;J</s=
pan>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-physconst-eV_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronvolt#cite_note-physconst-eV-1"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
Historically, the electronvolt was devised as a standard unit of measure th=
rough its usefulness in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particle_a=
ccelerator#Electrostatic_particle_accelerators" title=3D"Particle accelerat=
or">electrostatic particle accelerator</a> sciences, because a particle wit=
h <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_charge" title=3D"Electr=
ic charge">electric charge</a> <i>q</i> gains an energy <span class=3D"nowr=
ap"><i>E</i> =3D <i>qV</i></span> after passing through a voltage of <i>V</=
i>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition_and_use">Definit=
ion and use</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Electronvolt&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Defi=
nition and use"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>An electronvolt is the amount of energy gained or lost by a single <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron" title=3D"Electron">electron</=
a> when it moves through an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voltag=
e" title=3D"Voltage">electric potential difference</a> of one <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volt" title=3D"Volt">volt</a>. Hence, it has a =
value of one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volt" title=3D"Volt">=
volt</a>, which is <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"70001000=
00000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1&nbsp;J/C</span>, multiplied by the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_charge" title=3D"Elementary ch=
arge">elementary charge</a> <i>e</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<span class=3D"nowrap"><=
span data-sort-value=3D"6981160217663400000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.602<span sty=
le=3D"margin-left:.25em;">176</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">634<=
/span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>=
10<sup>=E2=88=9219</sup>&nbsp;C</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-physconst-e_2-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronvolt#=
cite_note-physconst-e-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Therefore, one electronvolt is equal t=
o <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6981160217663400000=E2=99=
=A0"></span>1.602<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">176</span><span style=
=3D"margin-left:.25em;">634</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-=
right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9219</sup>&nbsp;J</span>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-physconst-eV_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Electronvolt#cite_note-physconst-eV-1"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The electronvolt (eV) is a unit of energy, but is not an <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_unit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI un=
it">SI unit</a>. It is a commonly used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Unit_of_energy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unit of energy">unit of=
 energy</a> within physics, widely used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Solid-state_physics" title=3D"Solid-state physics">solid state</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_physics" title=3D"Atomic =
physics">atomic</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_physi=
cs" title=3D"Nuclear physics">nuclear</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Particle_physics" title=3D"Particle physics">particle</a> physi=
cs, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High-energy_astronomy" tit=
le=3D"High-energy astronomy">high-energy astrophysics</a>. It is commonly u=
sed with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_prefix" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"SI prefix">SI prefixes</a> <i>milli-</i> (10<sup>=E2=88=92=
3</sup>), <i>kilo-</i> (10<sup>3</sup>), <i>mega-</i> (10<sup>6</sup>), <i>=
giga-</i> (10<sup>9</sup>), <i>tera-</i> (10<sup>12</sup>), <i>peta-</i> (1=
0<sup>15</sup>), <i>exa-</i> (10<sup>18</sup>), <i>zetta-</i> (10<sup>21</s=
up>), <i>yotta-</i> (10<sup>24</sup>), <i>ronna-</i> (10<sup>27</sup>), or =
<i>quetta-</i> (10<sup>30</sup>), the respective symbols being meV, keV, Me=
V, GeV, TeV, PeV, EeV, ZeV, YeV, ReV, and QeV. The SI unit of energy is the=
 joule (J).
</p><p>In some older documents, and in the name <i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Bevatron" title=3D"Bevatron">Bevatron</a></i>, the symbol =
<i>BeV</i> is used, where the <i>B</i> stands for <i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Billion" title=3D"Billion">billion</a></i>. The symbol <=
i>BeV</i> is therefore equivalent to <i>GeV</i>, though neither is an SI un=
it.
</p>
