amental constants of importance in the theory are often used.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mass">Mass</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElectronvolt&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Mass"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>By <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass%E2%80%93energy_equivale=
nce" title=3D"Mass=E2=80=93energy equivalence">mass=E2=80=93energy equivale=
nce</a>, the electronvolt corresponds to a unit of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mass" title=3D"Mass">mass</a>. It is common in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particle_physics" title=3D"Particle physics">=
particle physics</a>, where units of mass and energy are often interchanged=
, to express mass in units of eV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup>, where <i>c</i> is th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speed_of_light" title=3D"Speed o=
f light">speed of light</a> in vacuum (from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mass%E2%80%93energy_equivalence" title=3D"Mass=E2=80=93energy equ=
ivalence"><span class=3D"nowrap"><i>E</i> =3D <i>mc</i><sup>2</sup></span><=
/a>). It is common to informally express mass in terms of eV as a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_mass" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Unit of mass">unit of mass</a>, effectively using a system of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_units" title=3D"Natural units">na=
tural units</a> with <i>c</i> set to 1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronvolt#cite_note-3"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilogram" title=3D"K=
ilogram">kilogram</a> equivalent of <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-=
value=3D"7000100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1&nbsp;eV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup=
></span> is:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
