</p><p>For example, an electron and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Positron" title=3D"Positron">positron</a>, each with a mass of <span cl=
ass=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6999511000000000000=E2=99=A0"></spa=
n>0.511&nbsp;MeV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span>, can <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Annihilation" title=3D"Annihilation">annihilate</a> to yiel=
d <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6987163742436971400=E2=99=
=A0"></span>1.022&nbsp;MeV</span> of energy. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Proton" title=3D"Proton">proton</a> has a mass of <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6999938000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>0=
.938&nbsp;GeV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span>. In general, the masses of all <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadron" title=3D"Hadron">hadrons</a>=
 are of the order of <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"700010=
0000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1&nbsp;GeV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span>, whic=
h makes the GeV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup> a convenient unit of mass for particle=
 physics:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Electronvolt#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"block-indent" style=3D"padding-left: 1.2em;"><span class=3D"n=
owrap"><span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7000100000000000000=
=E2=99=A0"></span>1&nbsp;GeV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span> =3D <span class=3D=
"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6973178266192000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.78=
2<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">661</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.2=
5em;">92</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=
=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9227</sup>&nbsp;kg</span>.</span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_mass_constant" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Atomic mass constant">atomic mass constant</a> (<=
i>m</i><sub>u</sub>), one twelfth of the mass a carbon-12 atom, is close to=
 the mass of a proton. To convert to electronvolt mass-equivalent, use the =
formula:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent" style=3D"padding-left: 1.2em;"><span=
 class=3D"nowrap"><i>m</i><sub>u</sub> =3D 1 Da =3D <span class=3D"nowrap">=
<span data-sort-value=3D"7002931494100000000=E2=99=A0"></span>931.4941&nbsp=
;MeV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span> =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort=
-value=3D"6999931494100000000=E2=99=A0"></span>0.931<span style=3D"margin-l=
eft:.25em;">4941</span>&nbsp;GeV/<i>c</i><sup>2</sup></span>.</span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Momentum">Momentum</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElectronvolt&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Momentum"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>By dividing a particle's kinetic energy in electronvolts by the fundamen=
tal constant <i>c</i> (the speed of light), one can describe the particle's=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Momentum" title=3D"Momentum">mome=
ntum</a> in units of eV/<i>c</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FNALunits_5-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronvolt#cite_n=
ote-FNALunits-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> In natural units in which the fundamental veloc=
ity constant <i>c</i> is numerically 1, the <i>c</i> may informally be omit=
ted to express momentum using the unit electronvolt.
</p>
