<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Distance">Distance</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DElectronvolt&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Distance"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particle_physics" title=3D"P=
article physics">particle physics</a>, a system of natural units in which t=
he speed of light in vacuum <i>c</i> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Planck_constant" title=3D"Planck constant">reduced Planck consta=
nt</a> <i>=C4=A7</i> are dimensionless and equal to unity is widely used: <=
span class=3D"nowrap"><i>c</i> =3D <i>=C4=A7</i> =3D 1</span>. In these uni=
ts, both distances and times are expressed in inverse energy units (while e=
nergy and mass are expressed in the same units, see <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mass%E2%80%93energy_equivalence" title=3D"Mass=E2=80=93en=
ergy equivalence">mass=E2=80=93energy equivalence</a>). In particular, part=
icle <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scattering_length" title=3D"S=
cattering length">scattering lengths</a> are often presented using a unit o=
f inverse particle mass.
</p><p>Outside this system of units, the conversion factors between electro=
nvolt, second, and nanometer are the following:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \hbar =3D1.054\ 571\ 817\ 646\times 10^{-34}\ \mathrm {J{\cdot =
}s} =3D6.582\ 119\ 569\ 509\times 10^{-16}\ \mathrm {eV{\cdot }s} .}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
